<section xml:id="section-special-solution-sets">

    <title>Special Solution Sets</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>Most of the time, a linear equation's final equivalent equation looks like <m>x=3</m>, and the solution set is written to show that there is only one solution: <m>\{3\}</m>. Similarly, a linear inequality's final equivalent equation looks like <m>x\lt5</m>, and the solution set is represented with either <m>(-\infty,5)</m> in interval notation or <m>\{x|x\lt5\}</m> in set-builder notation. It's possible that both linear equations and inequalities have all real numbesr as possible solutions, and it's possible that no real numbers are solutions to each. In this section, we will explore these special solution sets. We will start with video lectures.</p>

