    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Special Solution Sets</title>

<!--        <p>When we say <m>x=1</m> is a solution of the equation <m>x+2=3</m>, we imply that, when we substitute <m>x</m> with <m>1</m> in the equation <m>x+2=3</m>, the equation will be true.</p>

        <p>Similarly, when we say <m>x=2</m> is not a solution of the equation <m>x+2=3</m>, we imply that, when we substitute <m>x</m> with <m>2</m> in the equation <m>x+2=3</m>, the equation will be false.</p>

-->        <p>Recall that for the equation <m>x+2=5</m>, there is only one number which will make the equation true: <m>3</m>. This means that our solution is <m>3</m>, and we write the <term>solution set</term> as <m>\{3\}</m>. We say the equation's solution set has one <term>element</term>, <m>3</m>. <!--In advanced math courses, we will study <term>set</term> in details. For this course, we can simply understand <term>set</term> as <q>a group of numbers.</q>--></p>

        <p>We'll now explore equations that have all real numbers as possible solutions or no real numbers as possible solutions.</p>

        <example>
            <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>3x=3x+4</m>.</p>

            <p>To solve this equation, we need to move all terms containing <m>x</m> to one side of the equal sign:
                <md>
                    <mrow>3x\amp=3x+4</mrow>
                    <mrow>3x\subtractright{3x}\amp=3x+4\subtractright{3x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp=4</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>Notice that <m>x</m> is no longer present in the equation. What value can we substitute into <m>x</m> to make <m>0=4</m> true? Nothing! We say this equation has no solution. Or, the equation has an empty solution set. We can write this as <m>\emptyset</m>, which is the symbol for the empty set.</p>

            <p>The equation <m>0=4</m> is known a <term>false statement</term>, as it never holds true.</p>

<!--            <p>The equation <m>x=x+1</m> is asking: <q>Which number is the same as <m>1</m> more than the number itself?</q> It should make sense that no number can make this equation true.</p>
-->
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-solving-linear-equation-identity-intro">
            <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>2x+1=2x+1</m>.</p>

            <p>We will move all terms containing <m>x</m> to one side of the equal sign:
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x+1\amp=2x+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x+1\subtractright{2x}\amp=2x+1\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>1\amp=1</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>At this point, <m>x</m> is no longer contained in the equation. What value can we substitute into <m>x</m> to make <m>1=1</m> true? Any number! This means that are real numbers are possible solutions to the equation <m>2x+1=2x+1</m>. We say this equation's solution set contains <em>all real numbers</em>. We can write this set using set-builder notation as <m>\{x\mid x\text{ is a real number}\}</m> or using interval notation as <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.</p>

            <p>The equation <m>1=1</m> is known as an <term>identity</term> as it is always true.</p>

<!--            <p>The equation <m>2x+1=2x+1</m> is asking: <q>Which number is the same as that number itself?</q> It should make sense that any number can make this statement true.</p>
-->
        </example>

        <remark><p>
            What would have happened if when we obtained <m>1=1</m> in <xref ref="example-solving-linear-equation-identity-intro">Example</xref> we had continued solving? Here's what we could have obtained:
            <md>
                <mrow>1\amp=1</mrow>
                <mrow>1\subtractright{1}\amp=1\subtractright{1}</mrow>
                <mrow>0\amp=0</mrow>
            </md>
            As we can see, all we found was another identity&#8212;a different equation that is true for all values of <m>x</m>.
        </p></remark>

        <example>
            <p>Solve for <m>t</m> in the inequality <m>4t+5\gt 4t+2</m>.</p>

            <p>To solve for <m>t</m>, we will first subtract <m>4t</m> from each side to get all terms containing <m>t</m> on one side:
                <md>
                    <mrow>4t+5\amp\gt 4t+2</mrow>
                    <mrow>4t+5\subtractright{4t}\amp\gt 4t+2\subtractright{4t}</mrow>
                    <mrow>5\amp\gt 2</mrow>
                </md>
            Notice that again, the variable <m>t</m> is no longer contained in the inequality. We then need to conider which values of <m>t</m> make the inequality true. The answer is <em>all values</em>, so our solution set is all real numbers, which we can write as <m>\{t\mid t\text{ is a real number}\}</m>.</p>
        </example>

        <example>
            <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in the inequality <m>5x\le 5x-1</m>.</p>

            <p>To solve for <m>x</m>, we will first subtract <m>5x</m> from each side to get all terms containing <m>x</m> on one side:
                <md>
                    <mrow>5x\amp\le 5x-1</mrow>
                    <mrow>5x\subtractright{5x}\amp\le 5x-1\subtractright{5x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp\le -1</mrow>
                </md>
            Once more, the variable <m>x</m> is absent. So we can ask ourselves, <q>For which values of <m>x</m> is <m>0\le -1</m> true?</q> The answer is <em>none</em>, and so there is no solution to this inequality. We can write the solution set using <m>\emptyset</m>.</p>
        </example>


        <p>Let's summarize the two special cases when solving linear equations and inequalities:
        <list xml:id="list-special-solution-sets">
            <title>Special Solution Sets for Equations and Inequalities</title>
            <dl>
                <li><title>All Real Numbers</title>
                    <p>When the equivalent equation or inequality is an <em>identity</em> such as <m>2=2</m> or <m>0\lt2</m>, all real numbers are solutions. We write this solution set as either <m>\{x\mid x\text{ is a real number}\}</m> or <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.</p>
                </li>                
                <li><title>No Solution</title>
                    <p>When the equivalent equation or inequality is a <em>false statement</em> such as <m>0=2</m> or <m>0\gt2</m>, no real number is a solution. We write this solution set as either <m>\{\ \}</m> or <m>\emptyset</m> or write the words <q>no solution exists.</q></p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </list>
        </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Equations and Inequalities with Special Solution Sets</title>

        <p>Let's look at a more complicated example.</p>

        <example>
            <p>Solve for <m>a</m> in <m>\frac{2}{3}(a+1)-\frac{5}{6}=\frac{2}{3}a</m>.</p>

            <p>Solution:<md>
                <mrow>\frac{2}{3}(a+1)-\frac{5}{6}\amp=\frac{2}{3}a</mrow>
                <mrow>\multiplyleft{6}\frac{2}{3}(a+1)-\multiplyleft{6}\frac{5}{6}\amp=\multiplyleft{6}\frac{2}{3}a</mrow>
                <mrow>4(a+1)-5\amp=4a</mrow>
                <mrow>4a+4-5\amp=4a</mrow>
                <mrow>4a-1\amp=4a</mrow>
                <mrow>4a-1\subtractright{4a}\amp=4a\subtractright{4a}</mrow>
                <mrow>-1\amp=0</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>The statement <m>-1=0</m> is false, so the equation has no solution.</p>
        </example>

    </subsection>

