    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Inequalities with Special Solution Sets</title>

        <p>The solution for the inequality <m>x+2\gt3</m> is <m>x\gt1</m>. This implies, for inequality <m>x+2\gt3</m>, when we substitute <m>x</m> with any number greater than <m>1</m>, the inequality would be true. The solution set is <m>(1,\infty)</m>, which has infinitely many numbers.</p>

        <p>Similar to equations, there are two types of special solution sets when we solve inequalities. Let's look at some examples.</p>

        <example>
            <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>x\gt x+1</m>.</p>

            <p>To solve this inequality, we need to move <m>x</m> terms to one side of the inequality sign:<md>
                <mrow>x\amp\gt x+1</mrow>
                <mrow>x\subtractright{x}\amp\gt x+1\subtractright{x}</mrow>
                <mrow>0\amp\gt 1</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>What value can we substitute into <m>x</m> to make <m>0\gt1</m> true? Nothing! We say this inequality has no solution. Or, the inequality has an empty solution set.</p>

            <p>The equation <m>x\gt x+1</m> is asking: <q>Which number is greater than <m>1</m> more than itself?</q> It should make sense that no number can make this inequality true.</p>
        </example>

        <example>
            <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>x\le x</m>.</p>

            <p>To solve this inequality, we need to move <m>x</m> terms to one side of the inequality sign:<md>
                <mrow>x\amp\le x</mrow>
                <mrow>x\subtractright{x}\amp\le x\subtractright{x}</mrow>
                <mrow>0\amp\le 0</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>What value can we substitute into <m>x</m> to make <m>0\le0</m> true? Any number! We say this inequality's solution set is <q>all real numbers.</q></p>

            <p>The inequality <m>x\le x</m> is asking: <q>Which number is less than or equal to the number itself?</q> It should make sense that any number can make this statement true.</p>
        </example>

        <p>Let's summarize what we learned in this subsection.</p>
        <list>
            <title>Three Types of Solution Sets for Inequalities</title>
            <p>When we solve an inequality, there are 3 types of solution sets:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>When the last step looks like <m>x\gt a</m> where <m>a</m> is a real number, the solution is a set of infinitely many numbers, like <m>(a,\infty)</m>.</li>
                <li>When the last step is a false statement with no variable, like <m>1\le 0</m>, the inequality has an empty solution set. We can also say the inequality has <q>no solution.</q></li>
                <li>When the last step is a true statement with no variable, like <m>1\gt 0</m>, the solution set is <q>all real numbers.</q></li>
            </ul>
        </list>
    </subsection>

